<section id="about" class="fade-in">
  <span class="sec-lbl" id="lAbout">About Punjab</span>
  <h2 class="sec-title" id="aboutTitle">The <em>Land of Five Rivers</em></h2>
  <p class="sec-body" id="aboutBody">Punjab — Panj (five) + Aab (water) — is named for the five great rivers that carved its soul: the Jhelum, Chenab, Ravi, Beas and Sutlej. This is the land that fed empires, produced warriors who changed the course of Asian history, and gave the world one of its most joyous cultures. The Harappan civilization — one of the world's oldest — flourished here 5,000 years ago on the banks of these rivers. Punjab was the first land that Alexander the Great could not conquer; it was where he turned back at the Beas. The Sikh religion — born here in the 15th century through Guru Nanak Dev Ji — transformed Punjab into a land of fierce equality, selfless service (seva) and fearless courage (bir ras). The Golden Temple at Amritsar — Harmandir Sahib — is the spiritual heart not just of Sikhism but of all humanity; it serves the largest free community kitchen (langar) on earth, feeding 100,000 people every single day regardless of religion, caste or creed. Punjab's culture is an explosion of life — Bhangra music that makes the earth shake, folk traditions rooted in harvest celebrations, mustard fields stretching to every horizon in February, and a cuisine so rich and generous it has become the face of Indian food to the world. Post-1947, Punjab became the breadbasket of India — its farmers driving the Green Revolution that saved India from famine. Resilient, generous, loud and deeply spiritual, Punjab is India at its most alive.</p>
</section>

<section id="weather" class="fade-in">
  <span class="sec-lbl" id="lWeather">Climate &amp; Best Time</span>
  <h2 class="sec-title" id="weatherTitle">When to Visit <em>Punjab</em></h2>
  <p class="sec-body" id="weatherNote" style="margin-bottom:0">Punjab has four distinct seasons: a brief spring (Feb–Mar), blazing summer (Apr–Jun), monsoon (Jul–Sep) and a beautiful winter (Oct–Feb). October to March is ideal — the harvest festivals of Lohri and Baisakhi bookend the season, mustard blooms in February and the Golden Temple is at its most magnificent in winter light.</p>
